# Contracts

Contracts

Semantic backbone for federated but harmonized enterprise entities.

The contracts/ directory defines the structural truth layer of the enterprise operating model.

Contracts formalize canonical entity definitions, attribute authority, identity rules, and structural data quality expectations in a federated but semantically harmonized architecture.

These are not governance documents.
They are semantic agreements.

Each contract defines:

Canonical entity scope (e.g., Customer, Account, Policy, Transaction)

Identity key strategy and matching logic

Attribute-level designated and effective systems of record

Enrichment boundaries across systems

Structural data quality tiers tied to certification

AI eligibility gating criteria

Contracts sit upstream of:

PM artifacts

Certification workflows

Production readiness controls

Applied AI capabilities

They allow systems to remain operationally federated while harmonized through explicit semantic contracts.

Without contracts, federated systems drift.
With contracts, identity remains coherent across modernization cycles.

This layer defines what “complete and trusted” means before data is certified, transformed, or used for AI.
